name: 4-fluoroanisole
Reason:
To predict the melting point of 4-fluoroanisole we will consider the effects of its functional groups: 
The base compound, benzene, has a melting point of 5.5 °C. 
Adding a methoxy group (OCH3) typically makes the molecule more polar without significant increase in structural rigidity, thereby slightly decreasing the melting point. This may result in a -5 °C change. 
Adding a fluorine, which is an electronegative group, can increase the melting point due to the stronger dipole-dipole interactions it introduces, and possible hydrogen bonding with atmospheric moisture. The addition of fluorine may result in a +15 °C change. 
Overall, the competing effects of the methoxy and the fluorine groups will combine to determine the final melting point of the compound.
